{{wiktionary}}

In [[mathematics]] or [[science]] a '''formula''' is a [[rule]] or [[statement]] written in [[algebraic symbols]]. The [[plural]] of formula can be written in two ways: formulae or formulas - the choice is based on personal preference. 

Formulas use letters instead of words. A simple example of a formula is '''y = x'''. Here, if x is, for example, 1, then y = x so y = 1. Possibly the most famous formula is '''e = m × c <sup>2</sup>'''. [[Albert Einstein]] created this. In it, e is [[energy]], m is [[mass]] and c is the speed of [[light]]. Thus, energy = mass × (multiplied by) the speed of light <sup>2</sup> (squared). The multiplication sign is usually left out, giving '''e = mc <sup>2</sup>'''.

The <i>formula</i> '''e = mc <sup>2</sup>''' is also an [[equation]]. Every equation is a formula, but not every formula is an equation. For instance, the formula x≡y (x "is defined as" y) is not an equation because no "=" sign is used.

