[[Category:Mathematics]]

The '''Planck time''' is the length of [[time]] at which no smaller meaningful length can be validly measured due to the indeterminacy expressed in [[Werner Heisenberg]]'s [[Heisenberg's uncertainty principle|Uncertainty Principle]]. Theoretically, this is the shortest time measurement that is possible.<ref>Planck Time. COSMOS - The SAO Encyclopedia of Astronomy. Swinburne University. [http://astronomy.swin.edu.au/cosmos/P/Planck+Time]</ref> Planck time is roughly 10<sup>−44</sup> seconds. However, as of May 2010, the smallest time interval that was directly measured was 10<sup>−17</sup> seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2010/06/100624144109.htm|title=Delayed Time Zero in Photoemission: New Record in Time Measurement Accuracy|accessdate=3 September, 2012|publisher=ScienceDaily}}</ref><ref name="PlanckTime.">"Eyewitness Space, p 61"</ref> One Planck time is the time it would take a photon travelling at the speed of light to cross a distance equal to one [[Planck length]].
It is figured out from the [[Planck constant]], which was first thought of by the [[physics|physicist]] [[Max Planck]] in 1900. This work by Planck asserts that the energy of a photon is proportional to its frequency, and their relation can be put in terms of familiar units such as the [[joule]] by using the [[proportionality constant]] Planck gave us. Heisenberg's original quantum theory was improved by his teacher and colleague [[Max Born]]. Born put Heisenberg's equation into a [[Matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] form. Born immediately noticed that to calculate using these matrices one matrix had to be multiplied by another matrix. In matrix multiplication multiplying matrix P by matrix X gives a different result from the one obtained by multiplying matrix X by matrix P. He further noticed that the difference between the two matrices involves '''h''', the Planck proportionality constant. It shows that one can never pin down things like P (momentum) and X (location) exactly. It turns out that we cannot pin down a time any better than we can pin down a place or a momentum. We get closer and closer and then we reach the "Planck time."
