[[File:Kepler conjecture 2.jpg|thumb|One of the diagrams from ''Strena Seu de Nive Sexangula'', illustrating the Kepler conjecture]] The '''Kepler conjecture''' is a [[mathematics|mathematical]] [[conjecture]], about [[Sphere packing]] in three-dimnsional [[eucliean geometry|Euclidean]] space. It is named after [[Johannes Kepler]] (1571-1630) who first had this idea. Kepler supposed that the ways to pack [[sphere]]s of equal size that result in the packing with the highest [[density]] are [[Cubic crystal system|face-centered cubic]] or [[Hexagonal crystal system|hexagonal]] packings. These packings have a density of slightly over 74 percent, this means that they fill about 74 percent of space available.
