In [[mathematics]] and [[computer science]] the term '''Canonical form''', or sometimes '''Normal form''' refers to the usual representation of a mathematical object. For example, the canonical form of a [[positive integer]] in [[decimal representation]] is a [[finite set|finite]] [[sequence]] of [[digit]]s that does not begin with zero.
Mathematics has defined [[equivalence relation]]s for some objects. These equivalence realtions say that certain classes of objects are "equal". These objects then belong to the same [[equivalence class]]. In such a case, a canonical form consists in the choice of a specific object in each class. For example, [[row echelon form]] and [[Jordan normal form]] are canonical forms for [[matrix (mathematics)|matrices]]. {{math-stub}}
